#: course/lesson-1-what-code-is-like/lesson.bbcode:1
#. TRANSLATORS: Lesson header
msgid "What Code is Like"
msgstr "کد چگونه است"

#: course/lesson-1-what-code-is-like/lesson.bbcode:7
msgid "Learning to program can be daunting."
msgstr "آموختن برنامه‌نویسی می‌تواند دلهره‌آور باشد."

#: course/lesson-1-what-code-is-like/lesson.bbcode:8
msgid "Yet, you want to make video games, so [b]there is no way around learning to program[/b]. [i]Every[/i] video game is a computer program."
msgstr "با این همه، می‌خواهید بازی رایانه‌ای بسازید، پس [b]راهی جز آموختن برنامه‌نویسی نیست[/b]. [i]همهٔ[/i] بازی‌های رایانه‌ای برنامهٔ رایانه‌ای نیز هستند."

#: course/lesson-1-what-code-is-like/lesson.bbcode:7
#. TRANSLATORS: Heading
msgid "Telling the computer what to do"
msgstr "گفتن کارهایی که رایانه باید بکند به آن"

#: course/lesson-1-what-code-is-like/lesson.bbcode:9
#. TRANSLATORS: The "term" in [glossary term="<term>"] should NOT be
#. translated here
#, fuzzy
msgid "Programming is the process of writing precise [glossary term=\"instructions\"] that tell a computer how to perform a task."
msgstr "برنامه‌نویسی فرایند دقیق نوشتن دستورالعمل‌هایی است که به رایانه می‌گویند چگونه کاری را بینجامد."

#: course/lesson-1-what-code-is-like/lesson.bbcode:10
msgid "A game's instructions are, for example: moving a character, drawing a life bar, or playing a sound."
msgstr "برای نمونه: جنباندن شخصیت، کشیدن نوار جان یا پخش صدا از دستورالعمل‌های بازی هستند."

#: course/lesson-1-what-code-is-like/lesson.bbcode:11
msgid "To do any of that, you need to learn a [b]programming language[/b]: a specialized language to tell the computer what to do."
msgstr "برای انجام هرکدام از آنها، باید [b]زبان برنامه‌نویسی[/b] بیاموزید: زبانی ویژسته و مخصوص که به رایانه می‌گوید چه کاری بکند."

#: course/lesson-1-what-code-is-like/lesson.bbcode:23
msgid "Programming languages are different from natural ones like English or Spanish. The computer does not think. Unlike us, it can't [i]interpret[/i] what you tell it."
msgstr "زبان‌های برنامه‌نویسی با زبان‌های طبیعی همچون فارسی یا ایتالیایی تفاوت دارند. رایانه نمی‌اندیشد. به‌وارون ما نمی‌تواند چیزی که به آن می‌گویید را [i]تفسیر[/i] کند."

#: course/lesson-1-what-code-is-like/lesson.bbcode:24
msgid "You can't tell it something vague like \"draw a circle.\""
msgstr "نمی‌توانید چیزی گُنگ مانند «یک دایره بکش» به آن بگویید."

#: course/lesson-1-what-code-is-like/lesson.bbcode:25
msgid "Which circle? Where? Which color should it be? How big should it be?"
msgstr "کدام دایره؟ کجا؟ چه‌رنگی؟ چه‌اندازه‌ای؟"

#: course/lesson-1-what-code-is-like/lesson.bbcode:23
#. TRANSLATORS: Heading
msgid "The computer needs exact instructions"
msgstr "رایانه به دستورالعمل‌های دقیق نیاز دارد"

#: course/lesson-1-what-code-is-like/lesson.bbcode:31
msgid "To draw a filled circle, the computer needs to know exact drawing coordinates, the radius, the thickness, and color you want."
msgstr "برای کشیدن دایره‌ای توپر، رایانه نیاز دارد مختصات دقیق کشیدن، شعاع، ضخامت و رنگی که می‌خواهید را بداند."

#: course/lesson-1-what-code-is-like/lesson.bbcode:32
msgid "The code to do so [i]may[/i] look like this."
msgstr "کدی که چنین کند [i]شاید[/i] این شکلی باشد."

#: course/lesson-1-what-code-is-like/lesson.bbcode:33
msgid "[i]Click the button to run the code example and see the result.[/i]"
msgstr "[i]برای اجرای کد نمونه و دیدن نتیجه روی دکمه کلیک کنید.[/i]"

#: course/lesson-1-what-code-is-like/lesson.bbcode:41
msgid "In the following lessons, you'll learn how this code works."
msgstr "در آموزه‌های پیش‌رو، خواهید آموخت که این کد چگونه کار می‌کند."

#: course/lesson-1-what-code-is-like/lesson.bbcode:42
msgid "For now, we want to give you a sense of what computer code looks like. In this example, everything matters: each parenthesis, capital letter, period, and comma."
msgstr "فعلاً می‌خواهیم نشان‌تان دهیم که کد رایانه چی شکلی‌ست. در این نمونه همه‌چی مهم است: هر کمانک، حرف بزرگ، نقطه و کاما."

#: course/lesson-1-what-code-is-like/lesson.bbcode:43
msgid "The computer always does [b]exactly[/b] what you tell it to. No more, no less. It [i]blindly[/i] follows every instruction."
msgstr "رایانه همیشه [b]همانگونه[/b] که به آن می‌گویید عمل خواهد کرد. نه بیشتر، نه کمتر. [i]کورکورانه[/i] همهٔ دستورالعمل‌ها را دنبال می‌کند."

#: course/lesson-1-what-code-is-like/lesson.bbcode:44
msgid "[b]When you program, you're the one in charge, and you're free to do [i]anything[/i] you want.[/b]"
msgstr "[b]هنگامی که برنامه‌نویسی می‌کنید، شمایید که دارای اختیار هستید و آزادید [i]هر کاری[/i] که می‌خواهید بکنید.[/b]"

#: course/lesson-1-what-code-is-like/lesson.bbcode:41
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz question
msgid "How do you give instructions to a computer?"
msgstr "چگونه باید به رایانه دستورالعمل داد؟"

#: course/lesson-1-what-code-is-like/lesson.bbcode:41
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz explanation
msgid "Computers don't understand natural languages like English. To make them do anything, you need to give them precise instructions they understand, using a programming language."
msgstr "رایانه‌ها زبان‌های طبیعی مانند فارسی را نمی‌فهمند. برای اینکه وادار به هر کاری بکنیدشان، نیاز دارید با به‌کارگیری زبان برنامه‌نویسی دستورالعمل‌های دقیقی که می‌فهمند به آنها بدهید."

#: course/lesson-1-what-code-is-like/lesson.bbcode:41
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz answer
msgid "Using a programming language and precise instructions"
msgstr "به‌کارگیری زبان برنامه‌نویسی و دستورالعمل‌های دقیق"

#: course/lesson-1-what-code-is-like/lesson.bbcode:41
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz answer
msgid "Using prose in plain English"
msgstr "به‌کارگیری نثر انگلیسی"

#: course/lesson-1-what-code-is-like/lesson.bbcode:47
#. TRANSLATORS: Heading
msgid "You'll learn to code with GDScript"
msgstr "کدنویسی با جی.دی.اسکریپت را خواهید آموخت"

#: course/lesson-1-what-code-is-like/lesson.bbcode:55
msgid "In this course, you'll learn the GDScript programming language (the name stands for \"Godot script\")."
msgstr "در این دوره، زبان برنامه‌نویسی جی.دی.اسکریپت (کوتاه‌شدهٔ «گودوت اسکریپت») را خواهید آموخت."

#: course/lesson-1-what-code-is-like/lesson.bbcode:56
msgid "This is a language by game developers for game developers. You can use it within the Godot game engine to create games and applications."
msgstr "زبانی‌ست از بازی‌سازان برای بازی‌سازان. می‌توانید آن را درون موتور بازی‌سازی گودوت به کار ببرید و بازی و برنامه بسازید."

#: course/lesson-1-what-code-is-like/lesson.bbcode:57
#, fuzzy
msgid "It's the language used by games like [ignore][url=https://store.steampowered.com/app/1637320/Dome_Keeper/]Dome Keeper[/url] and [ignore][url=https://store.steampowered.com/app/1942280/Brotato/]Brotato[/url], and Godot also powers hits like [ignore][url=https://store.steampowered.com/app/2835570/Buckshot_Roulette/]Buckshot Roulette[/url] and [ignore][url=https://store.steampowered.com/app/2868840/Slay_the_Spire_2/]Slay the Spire 2[/url]."
msgstr "زبانی‌ست که بازی‌هایی همچون [ignore][url=https://store.steampowered.com/app/1637320/Dome_Keeper/]Dome Keeper[/url] (گنبدبان) و [ignore][url=https://store.steampowered.com/app/1942280/Brotato/]Brotato[/url] (بُروتِیتو) از آن بهره می‌برند."

#: course/lesson-1-what-code-is-like/lesson.bbcode:59
msgid "GDScript is an excellent language to get started with programming because it's specialized. Unlike some other languages, it doesn't have an [i]overwhelming[/i] amount of features for you to learn."
msgstr "جی‌دی‌اسکریپت به‌خاطر ویژسته و اختصاص‌یافته بودنش زبان بسیار خوبی برای آغاز کردن یادگیری برنامه‌نویسی‌ست. بر خلاف دیگر زبان‌ها، میزان [i]کلافه‌کننده‌ای[/i] ویژگی برای آموختن ندارد."

#: course/lesson-1-what-code-is-like/lesson.bbcode:59
#. TRANSLATORS: Heading
msgid "Most programming languages are similar"
msgstr "بیشتر زبان‌های برنامه‌نویسی شبیه‌اند"

#: course/lesson-1-what-code-is-like/lesson.bbcode:69
msgid "Don't be afraid of being locked in. The concepts you learn in your first programming language will apply to all the others."
msgstr "نگران گیر افتادن نباشید. مفهوم‌هایی که در نخستین زبان برنامه‌نویسی‌تان می‌آموزید در دیگر زبان‌ها نیز به کار خواهند آمد."

#: course/lesson-1-what-code-is-like/lesson.bbcode:70
msgid "Most languages have more similarities than differences. Once you learn one, it takes much less time to become productive with the next one."
msgstr "بیشتر زبان‌ها شباهت‌هایشان بیشتر از تفاوت و دگرسانی‌هایشان است. پس از آموختن یکی، برای کارآمد شدن در دیگر زبان‌ها زمان بسیار کمتری نیاز خواهد بود."

#: course/lesson-1-what-code-is-like/lesson.bbcode:71
msgid "Here's an example of the same code in three languages: GDScript, JavaScript, and Python."
msgstr "این نمونه‌ای از کدی یکسان در سه زبان است: جی‌دی‌اسکریپت، جاوا اسکریپت و پایتون."

#: course/lesson-1-what-code-is-like/lesson.bbcode:72
msgid "Try to spot the similarities and differences."
msgstr "بکوشید تا شباهت‌ها و دگرسانی‌های آن را بیابید."

#: course/lesson-1-what-code-is-like/lesson.bbcode:73
msgid "It doesn't look [i]that[/i] different, does it?"
msgstr "[i]آنچنان[/i] دگرسان نیست، هست؟"

#: course/lesson-1-what-code-is-like/lesson.bbcode:73
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz question
msgid "Are programming languages all completely different?"
msgstr "آیا زبان‌های برنامه‌نویسی همه به‌کاملی دگرسان‌اند؟"

#: course/lesson-1-what-code-is-like/lesson.bbcode:73
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz content
msgid "If you learn one language and then want to learn another, will you have to start from scratch?"
msgstr "اگر زبانی بیاموزید و سپس بخواهید یکی دیگر را بیاموزید، آیا نیاز دارید از صفر آغاز کنید؟"

#: course/lesson-1-what-code-is-like/lesson.bbcode:73
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz explanation
msgid "Most programming languages build upon the same ideas of how to program. As a result, they're mostly similar."
msgstr "بیشتر زبان‌های برنامه‌نویسی بر پایهٔ ایده‌های یکسانی دربارهٔ روش‌های برنامه‌نویسی ساخته شده‌اند. در نتیجه، بسیار شبیه‌اند."

#: course/lesson-1-what-code-is-like/lesson.bbcode:73
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz explanation
msgid "It's not to say all languages are the same, though. Some offer a really unique syntax and require a completely different mindset compared to GDScript."
msgstr "ولی اینگونه نیست که همهٔ زبان ها یکسان باشند. برخی دارای نحوی یکتا بوده و نیازمند نگرش دگرسانی نسبت به جی‌دی‌اسکریپت هستند."

#: course/lesson-1-what-code-is-like/lesson.bbcode:73
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz explanation
msgid "However, languages like GDScript, Python, JavaScript, C++, C#, and many others build upon a similar programming philosophy."
msgstr "با این همه، زبان‌هایی همچون جی‌دی‌اسکریپت، پایتون، جاوا اسکریپت، سی‌پلاس‌پلاس، سی‌شارپ و... بر پایهٔ فلسفهٔ برنامه‌نویسانهٔ یکسانی ساخته شده‌اند."

#: course/lesson-1-what-code-is-like/lesson.bbcode:73
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz answer
msgid "No, they have many similarities"
msgstr "نه، شباهت‌های بسیاری دارند"

#: course/lesson-1-what-code-is-like/lesson.bbcode:73
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz answer
msgid "Yes, they are completely different"
msgstr "آره، به‌کاملی دگرسان هستند"

#: course/lesson-1-what-code-is-like/lesson.bbcode:84
#. TRANSLATORS: Heading
msgid "This is a course for beginners"
msgstr "این دوره‌ای برای نوآموزان است"

#: course/lesson-1-what-code-is-like/lesson.bbcode:88
msgid "If you want to learn to make games or code but don't know where to start, this course should be perfect."
msgstr "اگر می‌خواهید بازی‌سازی یا کدنویسی بیاموزید ولی نمی‌دانید از کجا بیاغازید، این دوره بی‌کم‌وکاست خواهد بود."

#: course/lesson-1-what-code-is-like/lesson.bbcode:96
msgid "We designed it for [i]absolute beginners[/i], but if you already know another language, it can be a fun way to get started with Godot."
msgstr "این دوره را برای [i]نوآموزترین‌ها[/i] طراحی کردیم ولی اگر هم‌اکنون زبان دیگری هم می‌دانید می‌تواند راه جالبی برای راه افتادن در گودوت باشد."

#: course/lesson-1-what-code-is-like/lesson.bbcode:97
msgid "We will give you the coding foundations you need to start making games and applications with Godot."
msgstr "به شما پایه‌های کدنویسی‌ای که برای آغاز به بازی‌سازی و برنامه‌سازی با گودوت به آنها نیاز دارید را به شما خواهیم داد."

#: course/lesson-1-what-code-is-like/lesson.bbcode:98
msgid "Please be patient. It will take time before you can make your first complete game alone."
msgstr "خواهشمندیم شکیبا و صبور باشید. پیش از اینکه بتوانید به‌تنهایی نخستین بازی کامل‌تان را بسازید اندازه‌ای زمان خواهد برد."

#: course/lesson-1-what-code-is-like/lesson.bbcode:96
#. TRANSLATORS: Heading
msgid "Learning to make games takes practice"
msgstr "آموختن بازی‌سازی تمرین می‌خواهد"

#: course/lesson-1-what-code-is-like/lesson.bbcode:106
msgid "Creating games is more accessible than ever, but it still takes a lot of work and practice."
msgstr "بازی‌سازی از هر زمان دیگری دردسترس‌تر است، ولی هنوز نیاز بسیاری به کوشش و تمرین دارد."

#: course/lesson-1-what-code-is-like/lesson.bbcode:107
msgid "Do not expect any single course or book to turn you into a professional. [b]Programming is something you learn through practice.[/b]"
msgstr "انتظار نداشته باشید که با یک دوره یا کتاب تبدیل به بازی‌سازی حرفه‌ای شوید. [b]برنامه‌نویسی چیزی‌ست که از راه تمرین می‌آموزید.[/b]"

#: course/lesson-1-what-code-is-like/lesson.bbcode:108
msgid "If something doesn't make immediate sense, don't stress it too much! Keep learning and come back to it later."
msgstr "اگر چیزی را درجا نفهمیدید، نگران نباشید! به آموختن ادامه دهید و بعداً به آن برگردید."

#: course/lesson-1-what-code-is-like/lesson.bbcode:109
msgid "Enjoy the process and celebrate every little success. You will never stop learning as a game developer."
msgstr "از فرایند آموزش لذّت ببرید هر پیروزی کوچکی را جشن بگیرید. به‌عنوان بازی‌ساز هرگز دست از آموختن بر نخواهید داشت."

#: course/lesson-1-what-code-is-like/lesson.bbcode:106
#. TRANSLATORS: Heading
msgid "What and how you'll learn"
msgstr "چی و چجوری خواهید آموخت"

#: course/lesson-1-what-code-is-like/lesson.bbcode:110
msgid "In this free course, you will learn the foundations you need to start coding things like these:"
msgstr "در این دورهٔ رایگان، پایه‌هایی که برای آغاز به کدنویسی چیزهایی که در زیر می‌بینید به آنها نیاز دارید را خواهید آموخت:"

#: course/lesson-1-what-code-is-like/lesson.bbcode:128
msgid "Along the way, we'll teach you:"
msgstr "در درازای راه، به شما خواهیم آموزاند:"

#: course/lesson-1-what-code-is-like/lesson.bbcode:129
msgid ""
"- Some of the mindset you need as a developer. Too many programming courses skip that essential part.\n"
"- How to write GDScript code.\n"
"- Essential programming foundations to get you started."
msgstr ""
"- برخی از نگرش‌هایی که به‌عنوان توسعه‌دهنده نیاز دارید. دوره‌های برنامه‌نویسی بسیاری این بخش مهم را رد می‌کنند.\n"
"- چگونه کد جی‌دی‌اسکریپت بنویسید.\n"
"- پایه‌های مهم برنامه‌نویسی برای راه انداختن‌تان."

#: course/lesson-1-what-code-is-like/lesson.bbcode:130
msgid "As you go through the course, you will have many questions. We will answer them the best we can as we go."
msgstr "در طول این دوره، پرسش‌های بسیاری خواهید داشت. تا اندازه‌ای که بتوانیم آنها را در راه پاسخ خواهیم داد."

#: course/lesson-1-what-code-is-like/lesson.bbcode:131
msgid "But there is so much to cover that we have to take a few shortcuts. We don't want to [i]overwhelm[/i] you with information. We also want to respect the pace at which our brains memorize things."
msgstr "ولی چیزهای بسیاری برای پوشش دادن هست که باید به‌خاطرشان چند میانبر بزنیم. نمی‌خواهیم که شما را با اطلاعات [i]کلافه کنیم[/i]. همچنین می‌خواهیم سرعتی که مغزهایمان برای به خاطر سپردن اطلاعات نیاز دارد را در نظر داشته باشیم."

#: course/lesson-1-what-code-is-like/lesson.bbcode:132
msgid "We broke down the course into short lessons and practices. If we put too much into each part, you'd learn slower."
msgstr "دوره را به آموزه‌های کوتاه و تمرین‌ها بخش کردیم. اگر در هر بخش بیش از اندازه قرار می‌دادیم کندتر می‌آموختید."

#: course/lesson-1-what-code-is-like/lesson.bbcode:133
msgid "If at any time you're left with burning questions, you're more than welcome to join [url=https://discord.gg/87NNb3Z]our Discord community[/url]."
msgstr "هرگاه که با پرسش‌های داغی روبه‌رو شدید، در [url=https://discord.gg/87NNb3Z]انجمن دیسکوردمان[/url] قدمتان روی چشم‌مان خواهد بود."

#: course/lesson-1-what-code-is-like/lesson.bbcode:128
#. TRANSLATORS: Note title
msgid "Is this for Godot 4?"
msgstr "آیا این برای گودوت ۴ است؟"

#: course/lesson-1-what-code-is-like/lesson.bbcode:129
#. TRANSLATORS: Note content
msgid "What you'll learn in this free course is fully compatible with Godot 4. While we initially designed this series for Godot 3, the foundations of GDScript are still the same in Godot 4."
msgstr "چیزهایی که در این دورهٔ رایگان خواهید آموخت به‌خوبی با گودوت ۴ سازگار است. با اینکه در آغاز این دوره را برای گودوت ۳ طراحی کرده بودیم، پایه‌های جی‌دی‌اسکریپت در گودوت ۴ یکسان مانده‌اند."

#: course/lesson-1-what-code-is-like/lesson.bbcode:132
#. TRANSLATORS: Heading
msgid "Programming is a skill"
msgstr "برنامه‌نویسی مهارت است"

#: course/lesson-1-what-code-is-like/lesson.bbcode:142
msgid "Programming is a skill, so to get good at it, you must practice. It is why we built this app."
msgstr "برنامه‌نویسی مهارت است، پس برای بهتر شدن در آن باید تمرین کنید. دلیل ساخت این برنامه همین است."

#: course/lesson-1-what-code-is-like/lesson.bbcode:143
msgid "Each lesson is followed by an interactive practice to use what you learned."
msgstr "هر آموزه تمرینی تعاملی پس از خود دارد که با آن چیزی که آموختید را به کار ببرید."

#: course/lesson-1-what-code-is-like/lesson.bbcode:144
msgid "Speaking of which, it's time to look at the practice screen!"
msgstr "اکنون که بحثش پیش آمد، زمان آن رسیده است که نگاهی به صفحهٔ تمرین بیندازیم!"

#: course/lesson-1-what-code-is-like/lesson.bbcode:145
msgid "To continue, click the [i]Practice[/i] button below. It will give you a short run through how practices work."
msgstr "برای ادامه، روی دکمهٔ [i]تمرین[/i] در زیر کلیک کنید. به شما چکیدهٔ کوتاهی دربارهٔ چگونگی کارکرد تمرین‌ها خواهد داد."

#: course/lesson-1-what-code-is-like/lesson.bbcode:142
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice title
msgid "Try Your First Code"
msgstr "نخستین کدتان را بنویسید"

#: course/lesson-1-what-code-is-like/lesson.bbcode:142
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
msgid "We prepared a code sample for you. For this practice, you don't need to change anything."
msgstr "برای‌تان کد نمونه آماده کردیم. برای این تمرین، نیاز نیست چیزی را دگرگون کنید."

#: course/lesson-1-what-code-is-like/lesson.bbcode:142
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
msgid "To test the code, click the [i]Run[/i] button below the code editor."
msgstr "برای آزمودن این کد، روی دکمهٔ [i]اجرا[/i] در زیر ویراستار کد کلیک کنید."

#: course/lesson-1-what-code-is-like/lesson.bbcode:142
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice description
msgid "Run your first bit of code and see the result."
msgstr "نخستین تکهٔ کدتان را اجرا کنید و نتیجه را ببینید."

#: course/lesson-1-what-code-is-like/lesson.bbcode:142
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice hint
msgid "Click the [i]Run[/i] button."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-2-your-first-error/lesson.bbcode:1
#. TRANSLATORS: Lesson header
msgid "Your First Error"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-2-your-first-error/lesson.bbcode:13
msgid "When you program, you are bound to run into errors. Tons of them."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-2-your-first-error/lesson.bbcode:14
msgid "But you shouldn't worry! On the computer, [b]errors are a good thing[/b]."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-2-your-first-error/lesson.bbcode:15
msgid "You will encounter errors, and [i]that's okay[/i]: every programmer does. Especially professionals."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-2-your-first-error/lesson.bbcode:16
msgid "At school, maybe you learned that mistakes are a bad thing. When you code something, it's not the case: [b]errors help you write correct programs[/b] because they show you what is wrong in your programs."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-2-your-first-error/lesson.bbcode:17
msgid "A code error looks like this. It's a message that tells you some bit of your code doesn't work."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-2-your-first-error/lesson.bbcode:15
#. TRANSLATORS: Heading
msgid "Making errors friendlier"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-2-your-first-error/lesson.bbcode:23
msgid "Error messages can look a bit cryptic. This is because they're designed by programmers, for trained programmers."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-2-your-first-error/lesson.bbcode:24
msgid "We added an error translator in this app that will help you get started."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-2-your-first-error/lesson.bbcode:25
msgid "It shows you why an error happens and what the message means. It also gives you some tips on how to fix it."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-2-your-first-error/lesson.bbcode:31
msgid "Error messages are designed on purpose by fellow programmers who came before you. They anticipated you might have specific issues and wanted to help you fix them."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-2-your-first-error/lesson.bbcode:32
msgid "You shouldn't think of errors as failures. They are like mentors helping you from the past. Importantly, errors won't break your computer. At least not with GDScript because it's a pretty safe language."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-2-your-first-error/lesson.bbcode:33
msgid "Ultimately, you want to fix all the errors in your program. Understanding what is causing the errors, with the help of error messages, is key to fixing them."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-2-your-first-error/lesson.bbcode:31
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz question
msgid "Are error messages a good or a bad thing in code?"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-2-your-first-error/lesson.bbcode:31
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz explanation
msgid "Yes, error messages are here to help you!"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-2-your-first-error/lesson.bbcode:31
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz explanation
msgid "Pay attention to them, and do your best to read and understand them. With experience, you'll learn to make your code work more reliably thanks to error messages."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-2-your-first-error/lesson.bbcode:31
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz answer
msgid "They're bad: error messages are always bad."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-2-your-first-error/lesson.bbcode:31
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz answer
msgid "They're good: they're here to help."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-2-your-first-error/lesson.bbcode:41
msgid "Okay, let's see an error in action. Once again, click the [i]Practice[/i] button below to face your first real error."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-2-your-first-error/lesson.bbcode:41
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice title
msgid "Fix Your First Error"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-2-your-first-error/lesson.bbcode:41
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
msgid "This code is incorrect and will cause an error when you try to run it."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-2-your-first-error/lesson.bbcode:41
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
#. The "term" in [glossary term="<term>"] should NOT be translated here
msgid "The code defines an empty [glossary term=\"function\"] named [code]this_code_is_wrong[/code]."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-2-your-first-error/lesson.bbcode:41
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
#. The "term" in [glossary term="<term>"] should NOT be translated here
msgid "To work, the function should use the [glossary term=\"return\"] keyword. But this keyword is currently inside a comment, which the computer ignores."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-2-your-first-error/lesson.bbcode:41
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
msgid "Test the current code by pressing the [i]Run[/i] button."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-2-your-first-error/lesson.bbcode:41
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
msgid "Then, remove the comment sign (#) to make the code valid."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-2-your-first-error/lesson.bbcode:41
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
msgid "Be careful not to remove the spacing before [code]return[/code]! Otherwise, that'll cause another error. You may try that too, if you feel like it."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-2-your-first-error/lesson.bbcode:41
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice description
msgid "There's an error in this code. We need you to fix it!"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-2-your-first-error/lesson.bbcode:41
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice hint
msgid "Remove the # sign."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-3-standing-on-shoulders-of-giants/lesson.bbcode:1
#. TRANSLATORS: Lesson header
msgid "We Stand on the Shoulders of Giants"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-3-standing-on-shoulders-of-giants/lesson.bbcode:7
msgid "As programmers, we rely on a lot of code created by others before us."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-3-standing-on-shoulders-of-giants/lesson.bbcode:8
msgid "Every programming language comes with a wealth of features created by other programmers to save you time."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-3-standing-on-shoulders-of-giants/lesson.bbcode:9
#. TRANSLATORS: The "term" in [glossary term="<term>"] should NOT be
#. translated here
msgid "We call a bundle of code created by fellow developers a [glossary term=\"library\"]."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-3-standing-on-shoulders-of-giants/lesson.bbcode:10
msgid "It's a bunch of code sitting there, waiting for you to use it."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-3-standing-on-shoulders-of-giants/lesson.bbcode:11
msgid "Game engines like Godot bundle many libraries together. They provide a massive toolset to save you time when making games."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-3-standing-on-shoulders-of-giants/lesson.bbcode:13
#. TRANSLATORS: Heading
msgid "You'll always use a lot of existing code"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-3-standing-on-shoulders-of-giants/lesson.bbcode:17
msgid "When coding, you always use a lot of code from developers who came before you."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-3-standing-on-shoulders-of-giants/lesson.bbcode:18
#. TRANSLATORS: The "term" in [glossary term="<term>"] should NOT be
#. translated here
msgid "In a moment, you'll write your first code. You'll use [glossary term=\"functions\"] created by the Godot developers."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-3-standing-on-shoulders-of-giants/lesson.bbcode:19
#. TRANSLATORS: The "term" in [glossary term="<term>"] should NOT be
#. translated here
msgid "A function is a list of [glossary term=\"instructions\"] with an exact name. We can tell the computer to execute all the instructions in sequence with that name."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-3-standing-on-shoulders-of-giants/lesson.bbcode:21
#. TRANSLATORS: Heading
msgid "Calling functions"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-3-standing-on-shoulders-of-giants/lesson.bbcode:35
msgid "When you tell the computer to execute a function, we say you [i]call[/i] the function."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-3-standing-on-shoulders-of-giants/lesson.bbcode:36
msgid "To call a function, you write its [i]exact[/i] name followed by an open and closed parenthesis. To call the function named \"show\", you would write [code]show()[/code]."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-3-standing-on-shoulders-of-giants/lesson.bbcode:37
msgid "In Godot, calling [code]show()[/code] makes something visible, like a character or item. The complementary [code]hide()[/code] function hides the entity."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-3-standing-on-shoulders-of-giants/lesson.bbcode:38
msgid "Once an entity is visible, calling [code]show()[/code] again doesn't have any effect."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-3-standing-on-shoulders-of-giants/lesson.bbcode:39
msgid "Similarly, once you hide something, calling [code]hide()[/code] again doesn't change anything."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-3-standing-on-shoulders-of-giants/lesson.bbcode:40
msgid "[i]Click the Run button on any example below to execute the code listing.[/i]"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-3-standing-on-shoulders-of-giants/lesson.bbcode:39
msgid "In the code listing above, we write the function call [code]hide()[/code] in a new function named [code]run()[/code] to execute the code. Creating a new function is necessary to execute instructions in GDScript."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-3-standing-on-shoulders-of-giants/lesson.bbcode:39
#. TRANSLATORS: Note title
msgid "Can you tell me more about that \"run()\" function?"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-3-standing-on-shoulders-of-giants/lesson.bbcode:40
#. TRANSLATORS: Note content
msgid "In GDScript, unlike in some other languages, we must write our code inside of custom functions."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-3-standing-on-shoulders-of-giants/lesson.bbcode:41
#. TRANSLATORS: Note content
msgid "You'll learn what functions are and how they work in great detail in the course, but here's a quick look at them if you're curious."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-3-standing-on-shoulders-of-giants/lesson.bbcode:42
#. TRANSLATORS: Note content
msgid "A function is a bundle of code you can execute anytime. It's a named list of instructions."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-3-standing-on-shoulders-of-giants/lesson.bbcode:43
#. TRANSLATORS: Note content
msgid "To define a function, you need to write the [code]func[/code] keyword, the function's name, parentheses, and a colon: [code]func run():[/code] defines a function named [code]run()[/code]."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-3-standing-on-shoulders-of-giants/lesson.bbcode:44
#. TRANSLATORS: Note content
msgid "You then go to the next line to write the function's body. That's the instructions of the function."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-3-standing-on-shoulders-of-giants/lesson.bbcode:45
#. TRANSLATORS: Note content
msgid "Notice how each instruction starts with a leading [code]Tab[/code] character. The computer uses that to know which lines are part of the function."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-3-standing-on-shoulders-of-giants/lesson.bbcode:46
#. TRANSLATORS: Note content
msgid "Throughout the course, you'll see many functions called [code]run()[/code]."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-3-standing-on-shoulders-of-giants/lesson.bbcode:47
#. TRANSLATORS: Note content
msgid "Those are functions we created to give you interactive examples."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-3-standing-on-shoulders-of-giants/lesson.bbcode:57
#. TRANSLATORS: Heading
msgid "Function arguments"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-3-standing-on-shoulders-of-giants/lesson.bbcode:59
#. TRANSLATORS: The "term" in [glossary term="<term>"] should NOT be
#. translated here
msgid "We use parentheses to call functions because you can give the function [glossary term=\"arguments\"] inside the parentheses when calling it."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-3-standing-on-shoulders-of-giants/lesson.bbcode:60
#. TRANSLATORS: The "term" in [glossary term="<term>"] should NOT be
#. translated here
msgid "Here's a [glossary term=\"sprite\"] standing straight. If we call the [code]rotate(0.3)[/code] function, the character [i]sprite[/i] turns by 0.3 radians."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-3-standing-on-shoulders-of-giants/lesson.bbcode:77
msgid "The [code]0.3[/code] part between the parentheses is the function's [i]argument[/i]."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-3-standing-on-shoulders-of-giants/lesson.bbcode:78
msgid "Arguments are values (numbers, bits of text, and more) that change how the function behaves."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-3-standing-on-shoulders-of-giants/lesson.bbcode:79
msgid "Arguments let you fine-tune the effect of the function call. They can be optional at times, but functions often require arguments in order to work."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-3-standing-on-shoulders-of-giants/lesson.bbcode:80
msgid "For example, calling [code]rotate()[/code] without any argument would result in an error. Without an argument, Godot doesn't know by [i]how much[/i] you intend to rotate the [i]sprite[/i]."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-3-standing-on-shoulders-of-giants/lesson.bbcode:81
msgid "Don't worry about memorizing what arguments each function requires or accepts! As a programmer, the documentation will always be close by for you to refer to."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-3-standing-on-shoulders-of-giants/lesson.bbcode:82
msgid "Finally, notice how we use a dot in the number [code]0.3[/code] above: you need to use a dot like this to represent decimal numbers. You can't use commas as they have a different purpose in code."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-3-standing-on-shoulders-of-giants/lesson.bbcode:77
#. TRANSLATORS: Note title
msgid "What are radians?"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-3-standing-on-shoulders-of-giants/lesson.bbcode:78
#. TRANSLATORS: Note content
#. The "term" in [glossary term="<term>"] should NOT be translated here
msgid "The value of [code]0.3[/code] is an angle in [glossary term=\"radians\"]. In daily life, we're used to measuring angles in degrees. The radian is another scale commonly used in video games and math."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-3-standing-on-shoulders-of-giants/lesson.bbcode:79
#. TRANSLATORS: Note content
msgid "You can convert radians into degrees by multiplying them by 180 and dividing them by PI:"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-3-standing-on-shoulders-of-giants/lesson.bbcode:81
#. TRANSLATORS: Note content
msgid "An angle of [code]PI[/code] radians corresponds to [code]180[/code] degrees. And [code]2 * PI[/code] is a full turn: [code]360[/code] degrees."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-3-standing-on-shoulders-of-giants/lesson.bbcode:82
#. TRANSLATORS: Note content
msgid "[b]How do radians work exactly?[/b]"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-3-standing-on-shoulders-of-giants/lesson.bbcode:83
#. TRANSLATORS: Note content
msgid "Radians are a way to measure angles based on the radius of a circle."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-3-standing-on-shoulders-of-giants/lesson.bbcode:84
#. TRANSLATORS: Note content
msgid "To get the angle in radians, you take the circle's radius and wrap it around the circle. That angle is [code]1[/code] radian because you are wrapping the radius [code]1[/code] time around the circle."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-3-standing-on-shoulders-of-giants/lesson.bbcode:85
#. TRANSLATORS: Note content
msgid "Because the perimeter of a circle is [code]2 * PI * radius[/code], a full turn (360°) corresponds to [code]2 * PI[/code] radians: you need to wrap the radius of a circle [code]2 * PI[/code] times around the circle to make a full circle."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-3-standing-on-shoulders-of-giants/lesson.bbcode:95
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz question
msgid "What does the code below do?"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-3-standing-on-shoulders-of-giants/lesson.bbcode:95
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz explanation
msgid "Both answers were right! Technically, the code calls the [code]show()[/code] function. And doing so makes the game entity visible."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-3-standing-on-shoulders-of-giants/lesson.bbcode:95
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz answer
msgid "It calls the function named \"show\"."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-3-standing-on-shoulders-of-giants/lesson.bbcode:95
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz answer
msgid "It makes the entity (like a game character or a sprite) visible."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-3-standing-on-shoulders-of-giants/lesson.bbcode:108
msgid "Another example: With the [code]move_local_x()[/code] function, you can move the character to its left and right. The function takes one argument: a number of pixels to offset the entity."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-3-standing-on-shoulders-of-giants/lesson.bbcode:109
msgid "The complementary function [code]move_local_y()[/code] makes the character move up and down."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-3-standing-on-shoulders-of-giants/lesson.bbcode:110
msgid "This is one way to move a character in a game, although we'll see more powerful ways to do this later."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-3-standing-on-shoulders-of-giants/lesson.bbcode:110
#. TRANSLATORS: Note title
msgid "Why move_local_y(20) moves the character down"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-3-standing-on-shoulders-of-giants/lesson.bbcode:111
#. TRANSLATORS: Note content
msgid "With positive values ([code]20[/code]), the code above moves the robot to the right and down."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-3-standing-on-shoulders-of-giants/lesson.bbcode:112
#. TRANSLATORS: Note content
msgid "This is probably different than what you studied at school: in math classes, the horizontal axis points to the right, like here, but the vertical axis points up."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-3-standing-on-shoulders-of-giants/lesson.bbcode:113
#. TRANSLATORS: Note content
msgid "In video games, and generally in 2D computer graphics, the vertical axis points down instead. So whenever you move something on the Y-axis with a positive value, it'll move [i]down[/i]."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-3-standing-on-shoulders-of-giants/lesson.bbcode:118
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz question
msgid "How do you call a function?"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-3-standing-on-shoulders-of-giants/lesson.bbcode:118
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz content
msgid "What is the syntax you use to call a function in general?"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-3-standing-on-shoulders-of-giants/lesson.bbcode:118
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz explanation
msgid "To call a function, you need to write its exact name followed by an opening and a closing parenthesis."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-3-standing-on-shoulders-of-giants/lesson.bbcode:118
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz explanation
msgid "If the function requires one or more [i]arguments[/i], you add them inside the parentheses. Whether you need to do that or not depends on the function."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-3-standing-on-shoulders-of-giants/lesson.bbcode:118
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz answer
msgid "You write its name followed by an opening and a closing parenthesis."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-3-standing-on-shoulders-of-giants/lesson.bbcode:118
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz answer
msgid "You write its name followed by a colon."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-3-standing-on-shoulders-of-giants/lesson.bbcode:118
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz answer
msgid "You write a value, like a number, followed by an opening and a closing parenthesis."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-3-standing-on-shoulders-of-giants/lesson.bbcode:128
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice title
msgid "Make The Character Visible"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-3-standing-on-shoulders-of-giants/lesson.bbcode:128
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
msgid "Our robot character's invisible! Call the [code]show()[/code] function to make it appear."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-3-standing-on-shoulders-of-giants/lesson.bbcode:128
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
msgid "Please call [code]show()[/code] inside the [code]run()[/code] function, on line [code]2[/code], and keep the [code]Tab[/code] character at the start of the line. The computer needs that to understand your code."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-3-standing-on-shoulders-of-giants/lesson.bbcode:128
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice description
msgid "The robot's invisible! Call a function to bring it back."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-3-standing-on-shoulders-of-giants/lesson.bbcode:128
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice hint
msgid "Your code should call show() inside the run() function."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-3-standing-on-shoulders-of-giants/lesson.bbcode:146
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice title
msgid "Make the Robot Upright"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-3-standing-on-shoulders-of-giants/lesson.bbcode:146
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
msgid "The robot was turned by [code]-0.5[/code] radians. You need to make it upright by calling the [code]rotate()[/code] function."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-3-standing-on-shoulders-of-giants/lesson.bbcode:146
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
msgid "Please call [code]rotate()[/code] inside the [code]run()[/code] function, on line [code]2[/code], and keep the [code]Tab[/code] character at the start of the line. The computer needs that to understand your code."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-3-standing-on-shoulders-of-giants/lesson.bbcode:146
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice description
msgid "The robot is turned sideways. Help it straighten up with a function call."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-3-standing-on-shoulders-of-giants/lesson.bbcode:146
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice hint
msgid "You need to use the rotate() function, and give the proper arguments."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-3-standing-on-shoulders-of-giants/lesson.bbcode:146
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice hint
msgid "You need to call the rotate() function inside the run() function."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-3-standing-on-shoulders-of-giants/lesson.bbcode:146
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice hint
