msgid ""
"100\n"
"75\n"
"50\n"
"25\n"
"0\n"
"-25"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-13-conditions/lesson.bbcode:34
msgid "We can use conditions to run actions [b]selectively[/b]."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-13-conditions/lesson.bbcode:35
msgid "Conditions make your code branch into two paths: if the condition is met, the computer will run the corresponding instructions. Otherwise, those instructions will not run at all."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-13-conditions/lesson.bbcode:36
msgid "Video games and other computer programs are full of conditions. For example, game input largely relies on conditions: [i]if[/i] the player presses the button on a gamepad, the character jumps."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-13-conditions/lesson.bbcode:44
msgid "When the computer checks a condition, this is called [b]to evaluate[/b] a condition. All conditions [b]evaluate[/b] to either [code]true[/code] or [code]false[/code]."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-13-conditions/lesson.bbcode:45
msgid "Either the player is pressing the button, or not. Either the character is touching an enemy, or not."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-13-conditions/lesson.bbcode:46
msgid "In our case, [i]if[/i] the health goes over a maximum value, we want to reset it to the maximum."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-13-conditions/lesson.bbcode:47
msgid "To define a condition, we use the [code]if[/code] keyword. We write a line starting with [code]if[/code], [ignore]type the condition to evaluate, and end the line with a colon."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-13-conditions/lesson.bbcode:54
msgid "Notice the [code]>[/code] comparison sign. We read this symbol as \"greater than\"."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-13-conditions/lesson.bbcode:55
msgid "We've seen how function definitions use a colon at the end of the first line and nest content inside."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-13-conditions/lesson.bbcode:56
msgid "In GDScript, this syntax is a recurring pattern for all code blocks."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-13-conditions/lesson.bbcode:57
msgid "The computer knows which instructions belong to the condition because they are indented."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-13-conditions/lesson.bbcode:56
#. TRANSLATORS: Heading
msgid "Comparisons"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-13-conditions/lesson.bbcode:69
msgid "In the above example, we used the [code]>[/code] syntax to mean \"greater than\"."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-13-conditions/lesson.bbcode:70
msgid "We can compare numbers in other ways too."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-13-conditions/lesson.bbcode:71
msgid ""
"[code]>[/code] means \"greater than\"\n"
"[code]<[/code] means \"less than\"\n"
"[code]==[/code] means \"equal to\"\n"
"[code]!=[/code] means \"not equal to\""
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-13-conditions/lesson.bbcode:72
msgid "Here's how we might use these in [code]if[/code] statements."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-13-conditions/lesson.bbcode:71
#. TRANSLATORS: Note title
msgid "What does \"pass\" do in the code?"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-13-conditions/lesson.bbcode:72
#. TRANSLATORS: Note content
msgid "The [code]pass[/code] keyword prevents errors in our code when a line cannot be empty."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-13-conditions/lesson.bbcode:73
#. TRANSLATORS: Note content
msgid "For example, we must have a line of code after a function definition or an [code]if[/code] block. When you don't know what to write yet, you can use the [code]pass[/code] keyword as a placeholder, and Godot won't give any errors."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-13-conditions/lesson.bbcode:74
#. TRANSLATORS: Note content
msgid "In the previous example, if there was nothing below the [code]if[/code] lines, Godot would give us an \"Expected an indented block after 'if' \" error."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-13-conditions/lesson.bbcode:79
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz question
msgid "Which of these statements are true?"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-13-conditions/lesson.bbcode:79
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz explanation
msgid ""
"The comparison [code]3 > 1[/code] means \"three is greater than one\" which is [b]true[/b].\n"
"The comparison [code]2 < 3[/code] means \"two is less than three\" which is [b]true[/b].\n"
"The comparison [code]1 != 3[/code] means \"one is not equal to three\" which is [b]true[/b]."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-13-conditions/lesson.bbcode:79
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz explanation
msgid ""
"The comparison [code]2 == 1[/code] means \"two is equal to one\" which is [b]false[/b].\n"
"The comparison [code]3 < 1[/code] means \"three is less than one\" which is [b]false[/b]."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-13-conditions/lesson.bbcode:79
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz answer
msgid "3 > 1"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-13-conditions/lesson.bbcode:79
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz answer
msgid "2 == 1"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-13-conditions/lesson.bbcode:79
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz answer
msgid "2 < 3"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-13-conditions/lesson.bbcode:79
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz answer
msgid "1 != 3"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-13-conditions/lesson.bbcode:79
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz answer
msgid "3 < 1"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-13-conditions/lesson.bbcode:93
#. TRANSLATORS: Heading
msgid "Or else..."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-13-conditions/lesson.bbcode:99
msgid "The [code]if[/code] keyword comes with a complementary [code]else[/code] keyword."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-13-conditions/lesson.bbcode:100
msgid "You can write an [code]else[/code] block after an [code]if[/code] block, like so."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-13-conditions/lesson.bbcode:103
msgid "The [code]else[/code] block will run whenever the condition above it isn't met."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-13-conditions/lesson.bbcode:107
msgid "In the following practices, we'll use conditions and improve the way our character's health changes so it has limits."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-13-conditions/lesson.bbcode:107
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice title
msgid "Using Comparisons"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-13-conditions/lesson.bbcode:107
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
msgid "Each [code]if[/code] statement below has a wrong comparison sign. Fix the comparison signs so every condition is [code]true[/code] and every [code]print()[/code] message runs."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-13-conditions/lesson.bbcode:107
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
msgid "Only change the comparison signs ([code]>[/code], [code]<[/code], [code]==[/code], [code]!=[/code]). Do not change the values or the messages."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-13-conditions/lesson.bbcode:107
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
msgid "Here are the four comparison signs and what they mean:"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-13-conditions/lesson.bbcode:107
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
msgid ""
"[ul]\n"
"[code]>[/code]  Greater than\n"
"[code]<[/code]  Less than\n"
"[code]==[/code] Equal to\n"
"[code]!=[/code] Not equal to\n"
"[/ul]"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-13-conditions/lesson.bbcode:107
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
msgid "For example, if [code]health[/code] is equal to [code]100[/code] and the message says \"health is greater than five,\" the correct comparison is [code]health > 5[/code], because 100 is greater than 5. That makes the condition evaluate to [code]true[/code] and print the message."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-13-conditions/lesson.bbcode:107
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice description
msgid "Comparing values allows us to make decisions in code. But there's something wrong with these statements..."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-13-conditions/lesson.bbcode:107
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice hint
msgid "Read each [code]print()[/code] message carefully. The message tells you what the comparison should mean. Then pick the sign that matches best."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-13-conditions/lesson.bbcode:107
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice hint
msgid "Remember: you only need to change the [code]>[/code], [code]<[/code], [code]==[/code], or [code]!=[/code] symbols. Do not change numbers or the [code]print()[/code] calls!"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-13-conditions/lesson.bbcode:107
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice hint
msgid "For the last line, \"not equal to seven\" means you need the [code]!=[/code] sign: [code]health != 7[/code]."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-13-conditions/lesson.bbcode:149
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice title
msgid "Limiting Healing"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-13-conditions/lesson.bbcode:149
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
msgid "The [code]heal()[/code] function adds [code]amount[/code] to [code]health[/code]. But right now, health can increase forever, without limit! We want to stop it at [code]80[/code]."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-13-conditions/lesson.bbcode:149
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
msgid "I've defined a [code]health[/code] variable for you with a starting value of [code]20[/code]. Your task is to add a condition inside [code]heal()[/code] so that health is never greater than [code]80[/code]."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-13-conditions/lesson.bbcode:149
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
msgid "To check your code, I will call the [code]heal()[/code] function twice, like this:"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-13-conditions/lesson.bbcode:149
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
msgid ""
"[code]heal(40)[/code]\n"
"[code]heal(40)[/code]"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-13-conditions/lesson.bbcode:149
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
msgid "After those two calls, [code]health[/code] should be equal to [code]80[/code]."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-13-conditions/lesson.bbcode:149
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice description
msgid "As much as we might like, we don't want our robot to have too much health. Limit how much healing the robot can take."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-13-conditions/lesson.bbcode:149
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice hint
msgid "The starting code already adds the amount to the [code]health[/code] variable: [code]health += amount[/code] is already there. You need to add a check [b]after[/b] it, otherwise the health will overshoot your limit."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-13-conditions/lesson.bbcode:149
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice hint
msgid "Use [code]if health > 80:[/code] to detect when health went too high."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-13-conditions/lesson.bbcode:149
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice hint
msgid "Inside that [code]if[/code] block, set health back to the limit: [code]health = 80[/code]. That's how you limit the value."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-13-conditions/lesson.bbcode:178
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice title
msgid "Preventing Health from Going Below Zero"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-13-conditions/lesson.bbcode:178
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
msgid "We want to display the health number on screen, like in many RPGs. But currently, the health can go below 0, which does not make sense. We want to stop at [code]0[/code]."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-13-conditions/lesson.bbcode:178
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
msgid "Complete the [code]take_damage()[/code] function so it does two things:"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-13-conditions/lesson.bbcode:178
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
msgid ""
"1. Subtract [code]amount[/code] from [code]health[/code].\n"
"2. If [code]health[/code] is below [code]0[/code] after that, set it back to [code]0[/code]."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-13-conditions/lesson.bbcode:178
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
msgid "To check your code, I will call your [code]take_damage()[/code] function three times, like this:"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-13-conditions/lesson.bbcode:178
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
msgid ""
"[code]take_damage(10)[/code]\n"
"[code]take_damage(10)[/code]\n"
"[code]take_damage(10)[/code]"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-13-conditions/lesson.bbcode:178
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
msgid "After those three calls, [code]health[/code] should equal [code]0[/code], and not [code]-10[/code] or another value."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-13-conditions/lesson.bbcode:178
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice description
msgid "Having a negative health value doesn't make a lot of sense. Make sure the robot's health can't go below zero."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-13-conditions/lesson.bbcode:178
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice hint
msgid "Start by subtracting the damage: [code]health -= amount[/code]. This is how you apply damage."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-13-conditions/lesson.bbcode:178
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice hint
msgid "To limit the health, after subtracting the amount, you need to add a condition and reset the health."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-13-conditions/lesson.bbcode:178
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice hint
msgid "Here's how to write a condition to check if health went below zero: [code]if health < 0:[/code]."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-13-conditions/lesson.bbcode:178
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice hint
msgid "Inside the [code]if[/code] block, you can reset the health like this: [code]health = 0[/code]."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-14-multiplying/lesson.bbcode:1
#. TRANSLATORS: Lesson header
msgid "Multiplying"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-14-multiplying/lesson.bbcode:9
msgid "We define a [code]level[/code] variable to keep track of the level of the robot. It starts at level one."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-14-multiplying/lesson.bbcode:10
msgid "When the robot has defeated enough enemies, we call the [code]level_up()[/code] function to increment the robot's level."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-14-multiplying/lesson.bbcode:13
msgid "As we briefly saw in the last lesson, our robot could have a range of variables that could increase when it levels up."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-14-multiplying/lesson.bbcode:19
msgid "In this lesson, we'll just focus on increasing the robot's [code]max_health[/code]."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-14-multiplying/lesson.bbcode:20
msgid "The variable [code]max_health[/code] is the maximum amount the robot's [code]health[/code] can be. We change our [code]heal()[/code] function to use this variable."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-14-multiplying/lesson.bbcode:23
msgid "We could add [code]5[/code] to the [code]max_health[/code] every time the robot levels up."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-14-multiplying/lesson.bbcode:29
msgid "This would increase [code]max_health[/code] the same amount every time."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-14-multiplying/lesson.bbcode:30
msgid "If we graphed [code]max_health[/code], it'd look something like this."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-14-multiplying/lesson.bbcode:37
msgid "This growth is [b]linear[/b]."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-14-multiplying/lesson.bbcode:38
msgid "In our case, we want a feeling of more and more power as the robot levels up."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-14-multiplying/lesson.bbcode:39
msgid "We want a graph like this."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-14-multiplying/lesson.bbcode:47
msgid "This growth is [b]exponential[/b]."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-14-multiplying/lesson.bbcode:48
msgid "With each level, more [code]max_health[/code] is added than the previous level up."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-14-multiplying/lesson.bbcode:49
msgid "To get the exponential growth, we multiply the [code]max_health[/code] by an amount greater than [code]1[/code] each time the robot levels up."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-14-multiplying/lesson.bbcode:50
msgid "To multiply values together, we use [code]*[/code]."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-14-multiplying/lesson.bbcode:47
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz question
msgid "What is the value of damage?"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-14-multiplying/lesson.bbcode:47
#: course/lesson-14-multiplying/lesson.bbcode:63
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz content
msgid ""
"[code]\n"
"var level = 5\n"
"var power = 3"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-14-multiplying/lesson.bbcode:47
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz content
msgid ""
"func calculate_damage():\n"
"\tvar damage = power * level\n"
"[/code]"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-14-multiplying/lesson.bbcode:47
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz explanation
msgid "We multiply [code]power[/code] by [code]level[/code] using [code]*[/code] to get the result of [code]15[/code]."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-14-multiplying/lesson.bbcode:63
msgid "We can use [code]*=[/code] in the same way as [code]-=[/code] and [code]+=[/code]."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-14-multiplying/lesson.bbcode:63
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz question
msgid "What is the value of damage now?"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-14-multiplying/lesson.bbcode:63
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz content
msgid ""
"func calculate_damage():\n"
"\tvar damage = power * level\n"
"\tdamage *= 2\n"
"[/code]"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-14-multiplying/lesson.bbcode:63
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz explanation
msgid "The value of [code]damage[/code] starts as [code]15[/code]."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-14-multiplying/lesson.bbcode:63
#. TRANSLATORS: Quiz explanation
msgid "Then, [code]damage *= 2[/code] multiplies it by [code]2[/code] to get [code]30[/code]."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-14-multiplying/lesson.bbcode:82
msgid "Let's level up our robot and add exponential growth to [code]max_health[/code]."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-14-multiplying/lesson.bbcode:86
msgid "In the practices, you'll increase the robot's [code]max_health[/code] and add a special ability to our robot to make it extra tough at high levels."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-14-multiplying/lesson.bbcode:86
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice title
msgid "Increasing maximum health exponentially"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-14-multiplying/lesson.bbcode:86
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
msgid "Let's make the robot stronger when it levels up."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-14-multiplying/lesson.bbcode:86
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
msgid "Add to the [code]level_up()[/code] function so it does the following:"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-14-multiplying/lesson.bbcode:86
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
msgid ""
"- Increases [code]level[/code] by one.\n"
"- Increases [code]max_health[/code] by 10%."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-14-multiplying/lesson.bbcode:86
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice description
msgid "We want our robot to increase in strength as it levels up. Let's increase its health exponentially!"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-14-multiplying/lesson.bbcode:86
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice hint
msgid "To increase a number by 10%, multiply it by [code]1.1[/code]"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-14-multiplying/lesson.bbcode:110
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice title
msgid "Reducing damage at higher levels"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-14-multiplying/lesson.bbcode:110
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
msgid "When our robot's [code]level[/code] is [code]3[/code] or more, we want it to take a lot less damage."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-14-multiplying/lesson.bbcode:110
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
msgid "Add to the [code]take_damage()[/code] function so the following happens:"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-14-multiplying/lesson.bbcode:110
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
msgid "- [code]if[/code] the robot's [code]level[/code] is greater than [code]2[/code], reduce the damage [code]amount[/code] by 50%"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-14-multiplying/lesson.bbcode:110
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice goal
msgid "The robot is level 3. An enemy is going to attack for 10 damage. This damage should reduce to 5."
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-14-multiplying/lesson.bbcode:110
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice description
msgid "At higher levels, we want our robot to be super tough and take even less damage!"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-14-multiplying/lesson.bbcode:110
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice hint
msgid "You need to use an [code]if[/code] statement at the top of the function to check if the robot's [code]level[/code] is greater than [code]2[/code]"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-14-multiplying/lesson.bbcode:110
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice hint
msgid "To reduce the [code]amount[/code], multiply it by a value less than [code]1[/code]"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-14-multiplying/lesson.bbcode:110
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice hint
msgid "Reassign [code]amount[/code] on its own line inside the [code]if[/code] block, before the line [code]health -= amount[/code]"
msgstr ""

#: course/lesson-14-multiplying/lesson.bbcode:110
#. TRANSLATORS: Practice hint
msgid "Use [code]amount *= 0.5[/code] inside the [code]if[/code] block to reduce the damage by 50%"
